assets.description: I cannot imagine what it's like to be separated from my family after a harrowing journey to escape certain death. Argue as much as you please, but incarcerating youth is not a solution. So while we are caught up in the jargon of bible verses and adhering to the law, children are caught up in red tape, fear and the scarcity of love.

assets.displayName: We're Not Going to Take It!
assets.description: As we bear witness to the willful extinction of endangered species across the planet at our hands, I always come back to how we as a human species exact this kind of violence to each other. This senseless culling and displacement across every  tribal line imaginable. And I can only be heartened by the fact that it's the next generation that will be ready and motivated to fight this tide. This tide that threatens to swallow what's still good about us.

assets.description:
Captured from Cardiff Museum

"The body of the vase is made from a round Roman altar first recorded at Pozzuoli, near Naples, in 1489. A drawing in the British Museum shows it before its transformation into a vase in the eighteenth century.

The subject of the relief is the marriage of Paris, son of Priam of Troy, to Helen. Thomas Jenkins (1720-1798), a painter, banker and dealer in Classical antiquities based in Rome, probably bought this work in Naples in 1769."
